##Diary of the siege of Wuhan | Day 11

Techread

Features, Lanxi, founder of zhulu.com  , focuses on in-depth observations and business reviews of Internet startups, new media, and subcultures.

City time has finally entered the double-digit, medical resources are still not significantly improved.

In yesterday's "Caijing" Psycho, a designated hospital in Wuhan, for example, 120 patients with fever will be diagnosed with lung infection on average, and only five of them will be admitted to hospital, the rest were advised to go home and quarantine themselves.

Far from this disproportionate proportion, those who suffer from illness and psychological distress pile up a blizzard of messages for help, some people say that the example of Dareka no Negai Ga Kanau Koro beds being arranged because of the influence of Weibo is to encourage "allocation according to the order" , which can not be refuted for a while.

When you think about it, if the bed itself is empty, there's no reason why the hospital shouldn't admit a patient as a source of infection, that is, if for any reason, it's as if the call for help has been forwarded thousands of times, if we don't, we're going to be in a state of agitation, because when you allocate a bed, it means that the patient that the bed was meant to hold is now empty again.

There's no way to know if it's fair or unfair, and as I said before, it's not my place to blame every life that's been spent trying to survive.

The problem is that for patients who have no choice but to go home, that choice may also start to carry some external risks, as the virus is detected in the stool of patients with newly diagnosed pneumonia, is once again challenging the strength of the existing quarantine.

If the virus in faeces can spread through ventilation or sewage systems, it is unlikely that homes other than professional wards would be able to do the job of isolation, forcing people to go home because of the strain on medical resources, there are also huge risks.

We hope to be able to make a firm judgement on this concern at an early date.

At the same time, according to the "Xiaotangshan Model" , the two hospitals, Vulcan Mountain and Raytheon Mountain, have a total of more than 2,000 beds, which is almost equal to the daily number of newly confirmed cases in Hubei Province, the extent to which they can be used to relieve the stress of hospital visits when completed is not a matter for optimism.

At the very least, the two new hospitals are not the imaginary all-purpose button that, when pressed, will make all the disaster go away.

In fact, Xiaotangshan Hospital received a total of 680 SARS patients, its load today is unmatched, it proved the efficiency of centralized treatment, but can not help Wuhan and Hubei solve the number of difficulties.

Just yesterday, there were strangers in protective clothing in my neighborhood, who were taken to several buildings by security guards. No one knew what had happened.

Some people and condoms to get close to the answer is normal kill, the caliber is very uniform, but everyone's doubts still can not be dispelled, that the security may not tell the truth.

"The Tacitus trap" is not just a political concept. It is, by its very nature, the collapse of credibility, which leads to credulity being seen as a precondition for loss, once the public has decided that secrecy can be bought for security, they'll wonder if all the stability is real.

I also think of the patient who underwent brain surgery to hide his symptoms from the hospital, and who eventually led to almost all of the innocent doctors and nurses who participated in the surgery -- as if she didn't have to fight off a new pneumonia, the doctors who saved lives could never have imagined that they would meet such a fate.

Did you say the patient was deliberately trying to infect the paramedics who were trying to save his life with new coronary pneumonia? Definitely not. He was just afraid that if he told the truth, no one would ever want to open up his brain again, and, sure, maybe the doctors wouldn't abandon him, but he couldn't afford to.

And we all go down together.

Let's just say there's a lot to rebuild after this one.

This is my diary of the siege of Wuhan on the Eleventh Day.
